<TITLE> S Africa backs big electricity price increase </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 JOHANNESURG, March 20 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - South Africa's government on Thursday backed a plan to raise electricity prices more than 50 percent to tackle a power crisis hitting vital mines, despite fears it could fan inflation in Africa's biggest economy. State-owned power utility Eskom [ESCJ.UL] earlier this week asked South Africa's energy regulator for approval to hike electricity tariffs by 53 percent this year, angering consumers and raising concerns about inflation. But the government said it supported a tariff increase to help offset higher fuel costs and address a power crisis that has shut mines in the world's biggest platinum producer and plunged millions of homes into darkness. "South Africans must come to terms with the reality that it would be difficult for Eskom to continue to provide the cheapest electricity rate in the world," a cabinet statement said. The central bank governor said on Wednesday Eskom could find other ways to fund an expansion programme than to raise prices by such a large margin, saying such a hike would make it difficult to bring inflation back to a 3-6 percent target. Inflation reached a 5-year high of 8.8 percent year-on-year in January. Buoyant economic growth has in recent years seen millions of poor people living in black townships connect to power for the first time and Eskom is struggling to keep up with demand after years of underspending on generation capacity. The energy grid came close to collapse in January, forcing gold and platinum mines to shut down for five days, driving precious metal prices higher. A fresh power crisis this week threatened supplies to mines and prompted rolling blackouts in homes. The department of public enterprises said in a statement cash from the tariff increase would be used to pay for higher fuel costs not for expanding capacity. It said the poor and small businesses would pay le
